<!-- Tip from WOW -->


						<!-- <br clear=all><br><a name="tip"><img src="http://newsletters.fwpublications.com/newsletter_images/wdnl_reddot.jpg" width=440 height=1 border=0 align=center></a> 
						<br><B>HAVE FUN WITH DIALOGUE</b>
						<br><a href="http://www.writersonlineworkshops.com/specialoffers.asp?wdhomepage1200"><img src="http://newsletters.fwpublications.com/newsletter_images/wd_nl/broughttoyoubywow.gif" border=0></a>

						<p>Here are two exercises from the popular <b>Writing Effective Dialogue Workshop</b> from WritersOnlineWorkshops.com. 

						<p><ol><li>Many classic movies are remembered for famous lines of dialogue: "Frankly, my dear, I don't give a damn" (<i>Gone with the Wind</i>); "We'll always have Paris" (<i>Casablanca</i>); "You talkin' to me?" (<i>Taxi Driver</i>); "I'm walkin' here!" (<i>Midnight Cowboy</i>). 
						
						<p>Make a list of your personal favorite one-liners and think about why you like them so much. Then see if you can replace each one with a line that you think would be better.

						<p><li>You know those conversations you've had in your life that you later think of lines you'd wish you'd said?  Here's your chance. Write a conversation you had earlier today, transcribing it as accurately as you can remember. Then rewrite the dialogue, giving yourself better lines. Go back to older, more significant conversations&#151;that guy who dumped you in your favorite restaurant, that boss who fired you before you could tell him off&#151;and rewrite those.

						</ol>

						<p>The next session of the <b>Writing Effective Dialogue Workshop</b> starts on January 23rd. <a href="http://www.writersonlineworkshops.com/viewworkshop.asp?workshopid=1021"><b>Register now to reserve your space</b></a>. 

						-->
		

			
<!-- Hot Topics in WD Forum 

			            <br clear=all><br><a name="forum"><img src="http://newsletters.fwpublications.com/newsletter_images/wdnl_reddot.jpg" width=440 height=1 border=0 align=center></a> 
						
						<br><b>HOT TOPICS IN THE WRITERSDIGEST.COM FORUM</b>

						<p>New to the Discussion Forum on the <b>Writer's Digest</b> Web site:

						<P>In the <B>January issue</B> of <B>Writer's Digest</B>, Steven Goldsberry 
						critiques "Goddess in the Pillar," a manuscript provided by 
						Kevin L. Borgan. 

					<P>Goldsberry says character development is one aspect of 
						the story that needs reworking:

						<blockquote><P>"In chapter one of 'Goddess in the Pillar,' you present us with 
						a bunch of Daethons. Nice word, but what are they? What do 
						they look like? We're given clues. Daethons are multihumans, 
						but we don't find this out until the second page. What are 
						multihumans?

						<P>"Your story is intriguing, the pacing quick, and you make good 
						use of stock episodes. But you should consider how to better 
						present and describe your characters."</blockquote>

						<P><a href="http://www.writersdigest.com/forum"><B>Read an extended version of "Goddess in the Pillar,"</B></a> then offer your own 
						suggestions on how to bring to life Borgan's fictional 
						characters.

						

				
